 	<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
		<statement>
			<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.1.1) </p></aside>
				Let <me> A= \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 3\\ -2 \amp 5 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </me>. Find the following minors.
					<ol>
						<li><m>A_{1,1}</m>
						<hint>
							This is the <m> 2 \times 2 </m> matrix which results when the first row and column is deleted from <m> A </m>.
						</hint>
						<answer>
							<m>A_{1,1} = \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 3 \\ 5 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>.
						</answer>
						<solution>
						<m>A_{1,1}</m> is given by finding the matrix which results when the first row and column is deleted from <m> A </m>.
						<me> A_{1,1} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ 5 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </me>
						</solution> </li>
						
						<li> <m>A_{2,1}</m> 
						<hint>
							This is the <m> 2 \times 2 </m> matrix which results when the second row and first column is deleted from <m> A </m>.
						</hint>
						<answer>
							<m>A_{2,1} = \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 4 \\ 5 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</m>.
						</answer>
						<solution>
						<m>A_{2,1}</m> is given by finding the matrix which results when the second row and first column is deleted from <m> A </m>.
						<me>A_{2,1} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 5 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </me>
						</solution>
						</li>
						
						<li><m>A_{3,2}</m> <hint>
							This is the <m> 2 \times 2 </m> matrix which results when the third row and second column is deleted from <m> A </m>.
						</hint>
						<answer>
						<m>A_{3,2} = \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}</m>.
						</answer>
						<solution>
						<m>A_{3,2}</m> is given by finding the matrix which results when the third row and second column is deleted from <m> A </m>.
						<me>A_{3,2} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} </me>
						</solution>
						</li>
					</ol>	
						</statement>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->

						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: Adapted from <xref ref="ref-KK" />) </p></aside>
							Find the following determinant by expanding along the first row and the second column.
							<me> \det\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </me>
						</statement>

						 <hint>
							Recall how the signs of the terms in the cofactor expansion are affected by which row and column we use: <xref ref="fact-determinant-signs"/> and <xref ref="ex-determinant-signs" /> might help.
						</hint> 
						<answer>
						The determinant of the matrix is 2.
						</answer> 
						<solution>
						Expanding along the first row,
						<md>
							<mrow> \det(A) \amp = a_{1, 1}\det(A_{1,1}) - a_{1,2}\det(A_{1,2}) + a_{1,3}\det(A_{1,3})</mrow>
							<mrow>\amp = 1\det\begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1\end{bmatrix} - 2\det\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} + 1\det\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
							<mrow>\amp = 1((0)(1) - (1)(1)) - 2((1)(1) - (2)(1)) + 1((1)(1) - (2)(0)) </mrow>
							<mrow>\amp = 2</mrow>
						</md>.
						Expanding along the second column,
						<md>
							<mrow>\det(A) \amp = -a_{1,2}\det(A_{1,2}) + a_{2,2}\det(A_{2,2}) - a_{3,2}\det(A_{3,2})</mrow>
							<mrow> \amp = -2\det\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1\end{bmatrix} + 0\det\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1\end{bmatrix} - 1\det\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
							<mrow> \amp = -2((1)(1) - (2)(1)) + 0 - 1((1)(1) - (1)(1)) </mrow>
							<mrow> \amp = 2</mrow>
						</md>.

						</solution> 
						
					</exercise></p>

