					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->

						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.1.7) </p></aside>
							Compute the determinant by cofactor expansion.  Pick the easiest row or column to use.
							<me> \det\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2\\  2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </me>
						</statement>

						<hint>
							Recall how the signs of the terms in the cofactor expansion are affected by which row and column we use: <xref ref="fact-determinant-signs"/> and <xref ref="ex-determinant-signs" /> might help.
						</hint> 
						<answer>
							The determinant of the matrix is -4.
						</answer>
						 <solution>
							<p>We start by using the third row, because it gives us the most <m>0</m> entries (which result in 3x3 determinants that we can ignore!).
							<md>
								<mrow>\det\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2\\  2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \amp = 0\det\begin{bmatrix}0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 1\end{bmatrix} - 0\det\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} + 0\det\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1\end{bmatrix} - 2\det\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
								<mrow> \amp =  - 2\det\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
							</md>.</p>
							<p>
								Now we use the first row, again because we like the entries to be <m>0</m> as often as possible.
							<md>
								<mrow>\det\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2\\  2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \amp =- 2\det\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
								<mrow> \amp = -2\left(1\det\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 3\end{bmatrix} - 0\det\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 3\end{bmatrix} + 0\det\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}\right) </mrow>
								<mrow> \amp = -2(1((1)(3) - (1)(1))) </mrow>
								<mrow> \amp = -4 </mrow>
							</md>.  Thus the determinant is <m>-4</m>.</p>
						</solution> 
						
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->

						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.1.11) </p></aside>
							An operation is done to get from the first matrix to the second. Identify what was done and tell how it will affect the value of the determinant.
							<me> \begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \\  c \amp d \end{bmatrix} \to \ldots \to \begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \\  a+c \amp b+d \end{bmatrix} </me>
						</statement>

					 	<hint> 
						 Remember how row operations affect determinants: <xref ref="thm-row-ops-det"/>
						 </hint>  
						<answer> The first row is added to the second row.  The determinant of the resulting matrix is the same as the determinant of the original matrix. 
						</answer>
						<!-- <solution>
						</solution> -->
						 
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->

						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.1.12) </p></aside>
							An operation is done to get from the first matrix to the second. Identify what was done and tell how it will affect the value of the determinant.
							<me> \begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \\  c \amp d \end{bmatrix} \to \ldots \to \begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \\  2c \amp 2d \end{bmatrix} </me>
						</statement>

						 <hint> 
						 Remember how row operations affect determinants: <xref ref="thm-row-ops-det"/></hint>  
						<!-- <solution>
						</solution> -->
						<answer> The second row is multiplied by two.  The determinant of the resulting matrix will be twice as much as the determinant of the original matrix.
						</answer> 
					</exercise></p>
						<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->

						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.1.1) </p></aside>
							Compute the determinants of the following matrices.
							<ol cols="2">
							<li> <m> \begin{bmatrix} \cos(\theta) \amp -\sin(\theta) \\ \sin(\theta) \amp \cos(\theta) \end{bmatrix} </m> </li>
							<li> <m> \begin{bmatrix} 0  \amp a \amp 0 \\ b \amp c \amp d \\ 0 \amp e \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} </m> </li>
							<li> <m> \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp a \\ 0  \amp 0 \amp b \amp p \\ 0 \amp c \amp q \amp k \\ d \amp s \amp t \amp u \end{bmatrix} </m> </li> 
							</ol>
						</statement>

						 <hint> See <xref ref="def-2x2-determinant" /> for computing determinants of <m> 2 \times 2 </m> matrices. </hint>
						<hint>Recall how the signs of the terms in the cofactor expansion are affected by which row and column we use: <xref ref="fact-determinant-signs"/> and <xref ref="ex-determinant-signs" /> might help.</hint>
						<hint>The determinant of a triangular matrix is the product of the diagonal entries: <xref ref="fact-triangular-determinant"/></hint>
						 <hint> 
						 Remember how row operations affect determinants: <xref ref="thm-row-ops-det"/></hint>        
						<answer>
						<ol>
						<li> The determinant of the matrix in part (a) is 1. </li>
						<li> The determinant of the matrix in part (b) is 0. </li>
						<li> The determinant of the matrix in part (c) is abcd. </li>
						</ol>
						</answer> 
						<solution>
						<ol> 
						<li> <me> \det\begin{bmatrix} \cos(\theta) \amp -\sin(\theta) \\ \sin(\theta) \amp \cos(\theta) \end{bmatrix} = \cos(\theta)\cos(\theta)+\sin(\theta)\sin(\theta) =1 </me>. </li>
						<li> Using the first row, <me> \det\begin{bmatrix} 0  \amp a \amp 0 \\ b \amp c \amp d \\ 0 \amp e \amp 0 \end{vmatrix} 
						 = -a\det\begin{bmatrix}b \amp d \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
						= a (-1) (0) =0 </me>. </li>

						<li> We wish to interchange two rows in order to get an upper triangular matrix.  If we interchange two rows, then we must multiply the determinant of the resulting matrix by (-1) twice.  Once we have obtained an upper triangular matrix, we multiply the diagonal elements to get the determinant.
						 
						 <me> \det\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp a \\ 0  \amp 0 \amp b \amp p \\ 0 \amp c \amp q \amp k \\ d \amp s \amp t \amp u \end{bmatrix} = (-1)^2 \begin{bmatrix} d \amp s \amp t \amp u \\  0 \amp c \amp q \amp k \\ 0  \amp 0 \amp b \amp p \\  0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp a \end{bmatrix}  = abcd </me> </li>
						</ol>
						</solution>
						
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->

						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.1.6) </p></aside>
							Evaluate by cursory inspection:
							<ol cols="1">
							<li> <m>\det \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \amp c \\ a+1 \amp b+1 \amp c+1 \\ a-1 \amp b-1 \amp c-1 \end{bmatrix}</m> 
							<answer>
								The determinant of the given matrix is zero.
							</answer>
							<solution>
								We can subtract the first row from both the second and third row.
								<me>  \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \amp c \\ a+1 \amp b+1 \amp c+1 \\ a-1 \amp b-1 \amp c-1 \end{bmatrix}   \to  \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \amp c \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} </me> 
								Then we multiply the third row by -1 to obtain a matrix which has two rows that are the same.  Hence, the determinant of the original matrix would be (-1)(0) =0. 
								<me>  \det\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \amp c \\ a+1 \amp b+1 \amp c+1 \\ a-1 \amp b-1 \amp c-1 \end{bmatrix}=0  </me>
							</solution> 
							</li>
							<li> <m>\det \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \amp c \\ a+b \amp 2b \amp c+b \\ 2 \amp 2 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} </m> 
							<answer> 
								The determinant of the given matrix is zero.
							</answer>
							<solution>
								We subtract the first row from the second row.
								<me> \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \amp c \\ a+b \amp 2b \amp c+b \\ 2 \amp 2 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} \to   \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \amp c \\ b \amp b \amp b\\ 2 \amp 2 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} </me>
								Now if <m> b </m> is equal to zero, then we have a matrix with a row of zeros and hence the determinant must be zero.
								If <m> b </m> is not equal to zero, then we can multiple the second row by <m> \frac{2}{b} </m> to obtain a matrix which has two rows that are the same, and in this case the determinant must be zero as well.
								<me> \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \amp c \\ b \amp b \amp b\\ 2 \amp 2 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} \to   \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \amp c \\ 2 \amp 2 \amp 2\\ 2 \amp 2 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} </me>
								Therefore, the determinant of the matrix must be zero.
							</solution>
							</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>

						 <hint> 
						 Remember how row operations affect determinants: <xref ref="thm-row-ops-det"/></hint>  
						<hint>
						If two distinct rows (or columns) of A are identical, <m>\det(A) = 0 </m>
						</hint>
	 
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->

						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.1.15) </p></aside>
							<ol> 
							<li> Find <m> b </m> if <m>\det\begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp -1 \amp x \\ 2 \amp 6 \amp y \\ -5 \amp 4 \amp x \end{bmatrix} = ax + by.</m> 
							<answer><m>b=-15</m></answer>
							<solution> There are many ways to go about finding <m>b</m>, you may expand along various rows or columns.  For this solution, let us expand along the first row. 
							<md> 
								<mrow> \det(A) \amp = 5 \det\begin{bmatrix}6 \amp y \\ 4 \amp x \end{bmatrix} + 1 \det\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp y \\ -5 \amp x \end{bmatrix} + x \det\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 6 \\ -5 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = 5(6x-4y) + (2x+5y) + x(8 + 30) 
							</mrow>
							<mrow> \amp = 30x - 20y+ 2x+5y+38x</mrow>
							<mrow>\amp = 70x - 15y</mrow>
							</md>
							If <m> \det(A) = ax + by</m>, then <m>b = -15</m>
							</solution>
						</li>
							<li> Find <m> c </m> if <m>\det \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp x \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp y \amp 3 \\ -3 \amp z \amp 4  \end{bmatrix} = ax + by+cz.</m>
							<answer><m>c = -7</m></answer>
							<solution> As in the previous part (a), there are many ways to go about finding the answer by expanding along various rows or columns.  In this solution, we will expand along the first column.
							<md> 
								<mrow> \det(A) \amp = 2 \det\begin{bmatrix}y \amp 3 \\ z \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} -1 \det\begin{bmatrix} x \amp -1 \\ z \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} -3 \det\begin{bmatrix} x \amp -1 \\ y \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = 2(4y-3z) - (4x+z) + -3(3x + y) 
							</mrow>
							<mrow> \amp = 8y-6z-4x-z-9x-3y</mrow>
							<mrow>\amp = -13x +5y-7z</mrow>
							</md>
							If <m> \det(A) = ax + by+cz</m>, then <m>c = -7</m>
							</solution>
							</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>

						<hint>See <xref ref="fact-determinant-signs"/> for how determinants are computed along any row or column.</hint>
						<hint> See <xref ref="def-2x2-determinant" /> for computing determinants of <m> 2 \times 2 </m> matrices. </hint>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.1.17) </p></aside>
							Is it true that <m> \det(A+B) = \det(A)+\det(B) </m>? If this is so, explain why. If it is not so, give a counter example.
						</statement>
						<hint> Consider a <m> 2 \times 2 </m> matrix with positive entries and another with negative entries.
						</hint>
						<answer>
							There exists matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> such that <m>\det(A+B) \neq \det(A) + \det(B)</m> and so the statement of the exercise is false.
						</answer>
						<solution>
							There exists matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> such that <m>\det(A+B) \neq \det(A) + \det(B)</m>. Therefore, the statement of the exercise is false.  Let us show this with a counterexample.
							Let <m> A </m> be the identity matrix, <m> A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and let <m> B = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, then
							<me> \det(A+B) = \det\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}right) = \det(\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} \neq \det(A) + \det(B) = 1 + 1 =2 </me> 
						</solution>
						
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->

						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 3, Exercise 3.2.2) </p></aside>
							Use determinants to find which real values of c make each of the following matrices invertible.
							<ol cols="1">
							<li> <m> \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 3  \amp -4 \amp c \\ 2 \amp 5 \amp 8 \end{bmatrix} </m>
								<answer>
									The matrix will be invertible if <m> c </m> is not equal to <m> \frac{37}{5}. </m> 
								</answer>
								<solution> We know that the matrix is invertible if <m> \det(A) \ne 0 </m>, therefore we can compute the determinant in order to identify the values of <m> c </m> which make the determinant non-zero. 
									We choose to expand along the first row because the zero in the second column of the first row will simplify our cofactor calculation. 
									<md>
										<mrow>
											\det(A) = 1 \det\begin{bmatrix}-4 \amp c \\ 5 \amp 8 \end{bmatrix} + 0 + 3 \det\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -4 \\ 2 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix} \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											 (-32-5c) + 3(15+8) \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											-5c \amp \ne -37
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											c \amp \ne \frac{37}{5}
										</mrow>
										</md>
										The matrix will be invertible if <m> c </m> is not equal to <m> \frac{37}{5}</m>.
							 	</solution>
							</li>
							<li> <m> \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp c \amp -c \\ -1  \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ c \amp -c \amp c \end{bmatrix} </m> 
								<answer> The matrix will be invertiable if <m> c </m> is not equal to 0.
								</answer>
								<solution>
									We know that the matrix is invertible if <m> \det(A) \ne 0 </m>, therefore we can compute the determinant in order to identify the values of <m> c </m> which make the determinant non-zero. 
									We choose to expand along the first row because the zero in the first column of the first row will simplify our cofactor calculation. 
									<md>
										<mrow>
											\det(A) = 0 + -c\det\begin{bmatrix}-1 \amp 1 \\ c \amp c \end{bmatrix} + (-c)\det\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 2 \\ c \amp -c \end{bmatrix} \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											 -c(-c-c) + -c(c-2c) \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											3c^2 \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											c \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
									</md>
									The matrix will be invertiable if <m> c </m> is not equal to 0.
								</solution>
							</li>
							<li> <m>\begin{bmatrix} c \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0  \amp 2 \amp c \\ -1 \amp c \amp 5 \end{bmatrix} </m>
							<answer> The matrix will be invertible if <m> c</m> is not equal to 0, -3 or 3. 
							</answer>
							<solution>
									We know that the matrix is invertible if <m> \det(A) \neq 0 </m>, therefore we can compute the determinant in order to identify the values of <m> c </m> which make the determinant non-zero. 
									We choose to expand along the first row because the zero in the third column of the first row will simplify our cofactor calculation. 
									<md>
										<mrow>
											\det(A) = c\det\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp c \\ c \amp 5 \end{bmatrix} + -1\det\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp c \\ -1 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix} \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											 c(10-c^2) -(0-c) \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											c(9-c^2) \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											c \amp \ne 0,-3,3
										</mrow>
									</md>
									The matrix will be invertile if <m> c</m> is not equal to 0, -3 or 3.
							</solution>
							</li>
							<li> <m>\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp c \amp 3 \\ c  \amp 2 \amp c \\ 5 \amp c \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>
							<answer> Any real value <m> c</m> will make the matrix invertible because its determinant will always be equal to 2 regardless of the value of <m> c </m>. 
							</answer>
							<solution>
									We know that the matrix is invertible if <m> \det(A) \ne 0 </m>, therefore we can compute the determinant in order to identify the values of <m> c </m> which make the determinant non-zero. 
									We choose to expand along the first column this time just to mix things up.  
									<md>
										<mrow>
											\det(A) = 4\det\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp c \\ c \amp 4 \end{bvmatrix} + -c\det\begin{bmatrix} c \amp 3 \\ c \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}+ 5\det\begin{bmatrix} c \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp c \end{bmatrix} \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											 4(8-c^2) -(4c-3c) +5(c^2-6) \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											2 \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
									We know that the statement <m> 2 \amp \ne 0</m> is always true, regardless of the value of <m> c </m>, therefore the matrix is invertible for any real value of <m> c </m>
									</md>
							</solution>
							 </li>
							<li> <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ 0  \amp -1 \amp c \\ 2 \amp c \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </m>
							<answer> The matrix will be invertible as long as <m> c </m> is not equal to neither 1 nor 3.
							 </answer>
							<solution>
									We know that the matrix is invertible if <m> \det(A) \ne 0 </m>, therefore we can compute the determinant in order to identify the values of <m> c </m> which make the determinant non-zero. 
									We choose to expand along the first column because the zero in the second row of the first column will simplify our cofactor calculation. 
									<md>
										<mrow>
											\det(A) = \det\begin{bmatrix}-1 \amp c \\ c \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} + 2\det\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ -1 \amp c \end{bmatrix} \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											-1 - c^2 + 2(2c-1) \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											c^2 - 4c + 3 \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											c\amp \ne 1,3
										</mrow>
										The matrix will be invertible as long as <m> c </m> is not equal to neither 1 or 3. 
									</md>
							</solution>
							</li>
							<li> <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp c \amp -1 \\ c  \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp c \end{bmatrix} </m>
								<answer> The matrix will be invertible as long as <m> c </m> is not equal to -1. 
								</answer>
							<solution>
									We know that the matrix is invertible if <m> \det(A) \ne 0 </m>, therefore we can compute the determinant in order to identify the values of <m> c </m> which make the determinant non-zero. 
									We choose to expand along the third row this time because the zero in the third row of the first column will simplify our cofactor calculation. 
									<md>
										<mrow>
											\det(A) = -\det\begin{bmatrix}-1 \amp c \\ c \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} + c\det\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp c \\ c \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											-1(1+c) + c(1-c^2) \amp \ne 0
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											c^3 \amp \ne -1
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											c\amp \ne 1
										</mrow>
										The matrix will be invertible as long as <m> c </m> is not equal to neither -1. 
									</md>
							</solution>
							</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
						<hint> An <m> n \times n </m> is invertible if and only if <m> \det(A) \ne 0 </m> (<xref ref="thm-fundamental-determinant" />). 
						</hint>
